Based on my search results, I couldn't find any specific reference to a "keyword_feature" field mapping type in Elasticsearch. However, I found extensive information about Elasticsearch's dynamic field mapping capabilities and how they relate to the `keyword` data type. Here's what I discovered:

## Dynamic Field Mapping in Elasticsearch

The automatic detection and addition of new fields is called dynamic mapping.(no content)You can explicitly instruct Elasticsearch to dynamically create fields based on incoming documents by setting the dynamic parameter to true or runtime. When dynamic field mapping is enabled, Elasticsearch uses the rules in the following table to determine how to map data types for each field.

## String Fields and Keyword Mapping

When you set "dynamic":"true", Elasticsearch will map string fields as a text field with a keyword subfield. This means that by default, string fields get both text analysis capabilities and exact match capabilities through the `.keyword` subfield.

If you want to change this default behavior to map strings only as keywords, you can use dynamic templates:

If you are only indexing structured content and not interested in full text search, you can make Elasticsearch map your fields only as keyword fields.

## Dynamic Templates for Keyword Fields

Dynamic templates allow you greater control over how Elasticsearch maps your data beyond the default dynamic field mapping rules. You enable dynamic mapping by setting the dynamic parameter to true or runtime. You can then use dynamic templates to define custom mappings that can be applied to dynamically added fields based on the matching condition: match_mapping_type and unmatch_mapping_type operate on the data type that Elasticsearch detects · match and unmatch use a pattern to match on the field name · path_match and path_unmatch operate on the full dotted path to the field

An example of mapping all strings as keywords only would be:
```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "dynamic_templates": [
      {
        "strings_as_keywords": {
          "match_mapping_type": "string",
          "mapping": {
            "type": "keyword"
          }
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

## Dynamic Parameter Options

The dynamic parameter controls whether new fields are added dynamically, and accepts the following parameters: ... New fields are added to the mapping (default). ... New fields are added to the mapping as runtime fields. These fields are not indexed, and are loaded from _source at query time. ... New fields are ignored. These fields will not be indexed or searchable, but will still appear in the _source field of returned hits.

## Best Practices

Use explicit mappings: While dynamic mapping is convenient, it's always a good idea to define explicit mappings for fields that are known in advance. This ensures that the fields are mapped correctly and helps avoid potential issues with data type conflicts.(no content)Use dynamic templates: Custom dynamic templates can help you control the mapping of new fields and ensure that they are mapped correctly. Use dynamic templates to define custom rules based on field names, patterns, or data types.

